To save data to localStorage, we can use the `localStorage.setItem()` method which takes two parameters: a key and a value. The key is a string that will be used to identify the data in storage, and the value can be any type of JavaScript object (number, string, boolean, array, or object). Here's an example:

	localStorage.setItem("key", "value");

To read back from localStorage, we use the `localStorage.getItem()` method which also takes a key as its parameter and returns the value associated with that key (or null if the key is not found). Here's an example:

	var value = localStorage.getItem("key");

Here's an example of how we might use these methods to save and read back from storage:


	// Save data
	localStorage.setItem("name", "John Doe");

	localStorage.setItem("age", 30);
	localStorage.setItem("isLoggedIn", true);


	// Read back from storage
	var name = localStorage.getItem("name"); // "John Doe"
	var age = localStorage.getItem("age"); // 30
	var isLoggedIn = localStorage.getItem("isLoggedIn") === "true"; // true


Note that the `localStorage` object uses strings for both keys and values, so we need to convert data types back and forth as necessary. In this example, we used the string `"true"` for the value of `isLoggedIn`, but when we read it back we needed to use a comparison with a boolean value (`=== "true"`) instead of just using it directly as a boolean.
